  <p>The biggest price variable is <strong>strain and freshness.</strong> Standard, older stock runs €6–€8/g. Fresh, high-demand strains (OG Kush, Gelato, Runtz) sit at €10–€15/g. Exotic or imported strains at premium clubs can hit €15–€18/g.</p>

  <p>Hash is often the best value per gram but varies more by origin—Moroccan and European hash tends to be cheaper (€5–€8/g) while imported Lebanese or Afghan runs higher (€8–€12/g).</p>

  <p><strong>Bulk discounts are common.</strong> Most clubs offer 5–15% off if you buy 5g or more. A 10g purchase might drop to €85–€100 from €100–€120. Always ask—many tourists miss this because they don't expect it.</p>

  <h2 id="contribution-model">How the Contribution Model Works</h2>

  <p>This is the legal and practical core of Spanish cannabis clubs, and it's crucial to understand it correctly. You are <strong>not buying cannabis</strong> from a shop. You are making a monetary contribution to a nonprofit association in exchange for product.</p>

  <p>Here's how it actually functions:</p>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>You join the association.</strong> Pay membership fee (€20–€50). You're now a member of a registered collective with bylaws, a board, etc. It's a real legal structure, not a loophole.</li>
    <li><strong>The association grows cannabis collectively.</strong> Some clubs cultivate on-site. Others partner with external growers. The idea is that all cannabis is produced by/for the association members, not sold as a commercial product.</li>
    <li><strong>You make a "contribution" to cover costs.</strong> When you buy 1 gram, you're paying €8 to contribute to the collective's operational costs (electricity, rent, soil, seeds, staff). The gram itself is already yours as a member—you're just funding the system that grows it.</li>
    <li><strong>You receive your product.</strong> No invoice, no receipt necessarily (though most clubs will give you one). You walk out as a member who has contributed to your club's operating budget.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>The legal theory is that <strong>personal consumption associations are decriminalized in Spain</strong> as long as they remain nonprofit, noncommercial, and serve only members. The "contribution" language exists to maintain this legal distinction—you're not a customer buying from a business; you're a member contributing to a collective project.</p>

  <p>Is this a perfect legal gray area? Yes. Does it work in practice across Madrid? Also yes. Spanish courts have consistently upheld that personal consumption associations operating on this model are not breaking drug distribution laws, provided they:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Don't advertise publicly or aggressively recruit</li>
    <li>Only serve card-holding members (tourists can be members)</li>
    <li>Don't allow resale of cannabis outside the club</li>
    <li>Remain nonprofit</li>
    <li>Grow or source only for member consumption</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Legitimate clubs follow all of this. Scam operations or illegal dealers posing as clubs ignore it completely.</p>

