  <h2 id="hidden-costs">Are There Hidden Costs?</h2>

  <p>Short answer: Legitimate clubs, no. Scam operations, absolutely.</p>

  <p><strong>At legitimate Madrid clubs, the only costs are membership (one-time) and product contributions (per gram).</strong> What you should never encounter:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Mandatory "cover charges" to enter the lounge (different from membership)</li>
    <li>Forced purchase minimums</li>
    <li>Lockers/coat fees, lounge fees, or "entry taxes"</li>
    <li>Inflated prices for tourists vs. locals</li>
    <li>Bait-and-switch ("We show you one price, charge another")</li>
  </ul>

  <p>What some clubs do charge for (legitimately):</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Food/drinks:</strong> If a club has a café or vending machine, snacks/drinks cost extra. This is normal—around €2–€5 for a drink, €3–€8 for food. No different than any bar.</li>
    <li><strong>Rolling supplies:</strong> Some clubs sell papers, filters, or rolling trays. €1–€3 per item. Optional.</li>
    <li><strong>Lounge time (rare):</strong> A very small number of upscale clubs charge a lounge/seating fee on top of product—usually €5–€10 if you're just sitting and not buying much. This is transparency you can negotiate.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>The clearest way to avoid hidden costs: <strong>Ask the price before you order.</strong> Legitimate clubs will tell you a gram costs €8–€12 and a joint costs €6. If staff get vague or defensive about pricing, leave.</p>

