  <p>That budget assumes you visit clubs 2–3 times over three days and consume some product, share joints with others, etc. If you're lighter, you could go lower. If you're heavier, expect to spend more.</p>

  <p><strong>Payment methods:</strong> Most clubs are <strong>cash-only</strong> for product contributions. Bring euros. Some clubs accept Bizum (Spain's mobile payment app) but don't count on it. Membership fees sometimes accept card, but ask first. ATMs are everywhere in Madrid—withdrawal fees are only €1–€2, much cheaper than negotiating with a street dealer who takes only cash and potentially rips you off.</p>

  <p><strong>Timing tip:</strong> Prices are typically stable, but availability shifts. High-demand strains (Gelato, Wedding Cake) sell faster. If you know what you want, buy it earlier in your trip rather than leaving it for day three and finding it sold out.</p>

  <p><strong>Buying bulk:</strong> If you're staying longer than three days or traveling with friends, buying 20–30g at once often qualifies for bulk discount (10–15% off). That can save you €15–€30 across your stay—enough to offset membership fees entirely.</p>

  <p>Bottom line: Cannabis clubs in Madrid are <strong>more expensive than it looks on the surface</strong> when you factor in membership, but they're also infinitely safer, legal, and more reliable than any street alternative. For tourists, spending €200–€300 total on cannabis for a week-long visit is normal and reasonable, with the security and quality that price buys.</p>
